05218nam a22008655i 9783110747348DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021946830  a(OCoLC)1302164249  a97831107473487 a10.1515/97831107473482doi  a(DE-B1597)579754  a(OCoLC)1301546927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0410002bisacsh1 aFazaluddin, Shafi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConciliation in the Qurʾan :bThe Qurʾanic Ethics of Conflict Resolution /cShafi Fazaluddin. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XIII, 241 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIslam – Thought, Culture, and Society ,x2628-4286 ;v9  aPhD.cUniversity of Londond2020.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tNotes -- tIntroduction -- tConciliation in Context -- t1 Conciliation Discourse and Conflict Management Systems -- t2 Conciliation and Conflict in the Meccan and Medinan Qurʾan -- t3 The Notion of Iḥsān in Conflict Resolution -- t4 Conciliation Models and Conciliatory Appeal -- t5 Conciliation in Theory and Practice -- t6 Prophetic Disengagement and Social Justice -- tSummary Table: Groups 1–7 Conciliation Map of Key Themes -- tFinal Conclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConciliation in the Qurʾan addresses an existing imbalanced focus in Islamic Studies on conflict in the Qurʾan, and moves beyond a restrictive approach to ṣulḥ (reconciliation) as a mediation process in fragmented social contexts. The book offers a critical analysis of conciliation as a holistic concept in the Qurʾan, providing linguistic and structural insight based on the renowned pre-modern Arabic exegesis of Al-Rāzī (d. 1209) and the under-studied contemporary Urdu exegesis of Iṣlāḥī (d. 1997). This ambitious thematic study of the entire Qurʾan includes an innovative examination of the central ethical notion of iḥsān (gracious conduct), and a challenging discussion of notorious passages relating to conflict. The author offers solutions to unresolved issues such as the significance of the notion of iṣlāḥ (order), the relationship between conciliation and justice, and the structural and thematic significance of Q.48 (Sūrat Al-Fatḥ) and Q.49 (Sūrat Al-Ḥujurāt). Conciliation in the Qurʾan offers a compelling argument for the prevalence of conciliation in the Islamic scripture, and will be an essential read for practitioners in Islamic studies, community integration, conflict-resolution, interfaith dialogue and social justice.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aEthik. 4aKonflikt. 4aKoran. 4aVersöhnung. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Koran & Sacred Writings.2bisacsh  aConciliation.  aQurʾanic ethics.  aconflict.  aiḥsān.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022 Englishz978311099454408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022z9783110994537oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107474610 cprintz978311074720140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311074734840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110747348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110747348/original  a978-3-11-076682-0  DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  